DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0022-1996(86)90022-X
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/002219968690022X
AB  - This paper develops a two-country model in which the law of one price does not hold in the short run, and which is consistent with the stylized fact that exchange rates respond more quickly to ‘news’ than prices. This is done by assuming that firms face lumpy information costs in determining what price to charge. Both domestic and imported goods prices are therefore sticky with respect to ‘news’, and deviations from the law of one price (PPP) are due to exchange rate surprises. The model is used to analyze the domestic and international impact of real and nominal disturbances.
ER  - 

